23: The most commonly used git commands are:
24: add        Add file contents to the index
25: bisect     Find by binary search the change that introduced a bug
26: branch     List, create, or delete branches
27: checkout   Checkout a branch or paths to the working tree
28: clone      Clone a repository into a new directory
29: commit     Record changes to the repository
30: diff       Show changes between commits, commit and working tree, etc
31: fetch      Download objects and refs from another repository
32: grep       Print lines matching a pattern
33: init       Create an empty git repository or reinitialize an existing one
35: merge      Join two or more development histories together
36: mv         Move or rename a file, a directory, or a symlink
37: pull       Fetch from and merge with another repository or a local branch
38: push       Update remote refs along with associated objects
39: rebase     Forward-port local commits to the updated upstream head
40: reset      Reset current HEAD to the specified state
41: rm         Remove files from the working tree and from the index
42: show       Show various types of objects
43: status     Show the working tree status
44: tag        Create, list, delete or verify a tag object signed with GPG
46: See 'git help <command>' for more information on a specific command.
